
The ThreadObj is an abstract class that defines the basic mechanisms
for thread objects.  

int Group;

  The Group value specifies the priority queue into which the thread is
  placed.  This value can be changed dynamically, except when 
  the thread is in the ThreadReady state.

int bias;

  The bias value specifies the bias used by a weighted priority queue.

ThreadState state_flag;

  The state_flag value specifies the thread state:  ThreadReady, ThreadWaiting
  and ThreadBlocked.

MessageObj *message;

  The message value is a pointer to a message object constructed by the
  thread class which can be used for communication.

MPI_Status status;

  The status value is an MPI_Status object that can be used for asynchronous
  communication.

char* name;

  This is the character tag used to describe the thread during debugging.
  A default name is provided which incorporates the thread's id number.


ThreadObj(int Group_=0, int bias_=0, MPI_Comm comm=MPI_COMM_WORLD);
ThreadObj(MPI_Comm comm);

  The constructors can be provided with the group and bias information.  Additionally,
  they can be provided with the MPI communication group that is used
  for communication by the thread (this feature is not carefully used at the
  moment).

int run(double timelimit=-1.0)
 
  This method performs the basic execution of the thread.  The timelimit variable
  is a suggested time quanta for this thread (this is not a well-supported
  feature as the Scheduler object doesn't make intelligent suggestions about the
  timelimit).

ThreadState state()  {return state_flag;}
int ready()   {return (state()==ThreadReady);}
int blocked() {return (state()==ThreadBlocked);}
int waiting() {return (state()==ThreadBlocked);}

  The method state returns the current state of the thread.  The methods
  ready, blocked and waiting return TRUE if the current state matches the
  corresponding method name and FALSE otherwise.

void unready()

  This method is called after running the thread and is principly used to 
  modify the thread state.

void unblocked()

  This method is called after unblocking the thread and is principly used to 
  modify the thread state.

void unwaiting()

  This method is called after receiving a message that the thread was waiting for,
  and is principly used to modify the thread state.

int operator==(const ThreadObj& thread) {return (id == thread.id);}

  The operator== returns 1 if the thread id's match and 0 otherwise.



